### 2. Stratis Command Options
The `stratis` command follows a hierarchical structure: `stratis [target] [action]`.

#### ❶ Pool Management (`stratis pool`)
Used to manage the underlying block device collections.

| Command Option | Description | Example |
| :--- | :--- | :--- |
| `create` | Creates a new storage pool using empty block devices. | `stratis pool create my_pool /dev/sdb` |
| `list` | Displays all existing Stratis pools and their usage. | `stratis pool list` |
| `add-data` | Adds additional block devices to scale up an existing pool. | `stratis pool add-data my_pool /dev/sdc` |
| `rename` | Renames an existing pool. | `stratis pool rename old_name new_name` |
| `destroy` | Deletes a pool (Only works if all child filesystems are deleted). | `stratis pool destroy my_pool` |

#### ❷ Filesystem Management (`stratis filesystem`)
Used to manage actual mountable file systems inside a pool.

| Command Option | Description | Example |
| :--- | :--- | :--- |
| `create` | Creates a thin-provisioned filesystem inside a pool. | `stratis filesystem create my_pool my_fs` |
| `list` | Lists filesystems, including their unique device paths. | `stratis filesystem list` |
| `snapshot` | Creates a read/writeable snapshot of a filesystem. | `stratis filesystem snapshot my_pool my_fs snap_my_fs` |
| `destroy` | Permanently deletes a filesystem. | `stratis filesystem destroy my_pool my_fs` |

